   newsPolitics

Andrew Yang challenges Sen. Ted Cruz in basketball, and Cruz tells him to
bring it

The Democratic candidate for president is in Houston, the senator's hometown,
for the debate Thursday night.

   Sen. Ted Cruz dribbled past Jimmy Kimmel during the Blobfish Basketball
   Classic and one-on-one interview at Texas Southern University's Health
   & Physical Education Arena in June 2018 in Houston. Cruz challenged
   Kimmel to the game after Kimmel blamed the Houston Rockets playoff loss
   on the senator. Cruz won 11-9.
   Sen. Ted Cruz dribbled past Jimmy Kimmel during the Blobfish Basketball
   Classic and one-on-one interview at Texas Southern University's Health
   & Physical Education Arena in June 2018 in Houston. Cruz challenged
   Kimmel to the game after Kimmel blamed the Houston Rockets playoff loss
   on the senator. Cruz won 11-9.(Michael Ciaglo / AP)

   By Paul Cobler

   4:06 PM on Sep 12, 2019

   WASHINGTON — Texas Sen. Ted Cruz and Democratic presidential candidate
   Andrew Yang are about to settle their partisan differences the old
   fashioned way: a one-on-one game of basketball.

   The idea for the game was born on Twitter when a Fox News producer
   replied to a video of Yang playing basketball, saying Cruz and Yang
   should play each other.

   Cruz quickly dismissed the idea.

   "Sorry. You gotta poll at 5% or more to play on my court," Cruz
   tweeted.

     Sorry. You gotta poll at 5% or more to play on my court.
     https://t.co/xRx6VYdWft
     — Ted Cruz (@tedcruz) September 11, 2019

   Yang replied, pointing out that he was polling at exactly 5% in a
   recent poll by The Hill and Harris X, and telling Cruz he would be
   "delighted to beat you in basketball."

   Cruz tweeted a gif telling Yang to "bring it." They publicly hammered
   out the rules of engagement, settling on a one-on-one format in Houston
   sometime Friday afternoon. Yang, an entrepreneur and former technology
   executive, will be in Houston, Cruz's hometown, for the Democratic
   primary debate Thursday evening.

     Hmm. You’re taller than I am. From the video, you’re probably a
     better shot. And, I’ve seen you dunking (on an 8-foot rim).
     Altogether, pretty strong. So....... https://t.co/hVlhDfKS1W
     pic.twitter.com/cMepUnKWlu
     — Ted Cruz (@tedcruz) September 12, 2019

   The loser will donate $5,000 to a nonpolitical charity of the winner's
   choice.

   Cruz confirmed Thursday morning that the game is on.
   hidden ad unit
{"unitName":"dfpPosition1","display":"mobile","isMobile":false}

   "I think so. Right before I walked in, I accepted," Cruz told a group
   of reporters at a breakfast hosted by The Christian Science Monitor.

   The Yang campaign did not immediately respond to a request for comment.

   Cruz has played this game before. Last June, the senator challenged
   late-night talk show host Jimmy Kimmel to a game of one-on-one,
   defeating him 11-9. The News said the game could only be described
   as "some really bad basketball," with Cruz and Kimmel taking more than
   100 shots to get to that scoreline.

   Despite his win, Cruz appears to be positioning himself as the
   underdog, pointing out Yang's height advantage, superior shot form and
   ability to dunk on an 8-foot rim.

   "Look, the guy is, I'm pretty sure, taller than I am," Cruz said. "At
   least from online, it looks like he has a good shot. He's probably a
   better ball player than I am. It's part of why I suggested
   four-on-four. ... I think it would have been a better game and more
   fun. ... But I'm more than happy to do it."
   [f896a1ce-d49d-4616-9c94-f305ee632a3d.JPG]

   Paul Cobler, Politics Reporting Fellow. Paul Cobler covers politics for
   The Dallas Morning News in Washington, DC. Paul is a recent graduate of
   the University of Texas at Austin with a degree in journalism. While
   there, he worked at the school's student newspaper, The Daily Texan,
   and interned for newspapers across the state.
   paul.cobler@dallasnews.com @PaulCobler

